woy, leading Canadian sociologists continue the conversation by discussing not only how and why they should do sociology but also how ethical judgments influence sociological practice and the evaluation of research. Most importantly, they ask whether and under what circumstances sociologists should advocate for social change. Regardless of whether they focus on activism, research, theory, or teaching, the contributors offer insights into where the discipline is heading and why it matters to people inside and outside the university.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aApplied sociology. 0aSociologyxMethodology. 0aSociologyxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aSociologyxPhilosophy. 0aSociologyxStudy and teaching. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aBerg, Axel Van Den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBucklaschuk, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurawoy, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanemaayer, Ariane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanemaayer, Ariane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHelmes-Hayes, Rick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMesny, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilne, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNolan, Kyle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrentice, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaffer, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Christopher J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Christopher J., eeditor.4edt4http